. Both eventually reached home by different routes, and their dramatic narratives caught the public imagination. Byronwas the grandfather of the poet, Lord Byron, who much admired the book and based the shipwreck scenes in Don Juan on 'my grand-dad's Narrative'. This voyage was the basis for Patrick O'Brian's historical work The Unknown Shore, written before he embarked on the Jack Aubrey novels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aShipwreckszChilazChiloé. 0aShipwreckszChilazChiloé. 0aVoyages and travelsvEarly works to 1800. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh1 aByron, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGurney, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846152511?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846152511423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846152511/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles